{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480360"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:41:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:41:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"43"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/43"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.03,0.14,0.81,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"43"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47289"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/43"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"43"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32001"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"121"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12354"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12355"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47289","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47289"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 72-year-old man has a CT\u00a0scan performed for suspected diverticulitis. The scan is normal apart from a 1.5 cm solid mass in the lower pole of his right kidney. This is assumed to be an incidental finding.\u00a0No other abnormalities are found on the CT\u00a0and there is no evidence of local invasion or metastatic disease. The man has no significant medical history and does not take any medications. He is a non-smoker and drinks two glasses of wine at weekends. The physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cryoablation","Right nephrectomy","Partial nephrectomy","Active surveillance","Radiofrequency ablation"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is an example of a common clinical problem known as the small renal mass. Given the increased utilisation of cross-sectional imaging of the abdomen for many indications there are increasing numbers of small renal lesions being identified which may or may not represent a clinically significant malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERenal cell carcinoma (RCC) is suggested on CT imaging by the presence of a solid enhancing (\u0026gt;20 Hounsfield units difference between contrast and non-contrast phases) or complex cystic mass arising from the parenchyma of the kidney. The risk of metastatic disease with an RCC \u0026lt;3cm is small and the annual rate of metastases is 1%. Furthermore, some low-grade malignancies are slow to progress and may stay stable for many years. In the first instance \u003Cstrong\u003Esurveillance\u003C/strong\u003E of this mass is completely reasonable. A contrast-enhanced CT scan should be repeated in six months time to re-evaluate the lesion and establish a growth rate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor tumours larger than 4cm, some form of resection should be considered and this may be a \u003Cstrong\u003Etotal\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Epartial nephrectomy\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESome form of ablation therapy (\u003Cstrong\u003Ecryoablation\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eradiofrequency\u003C/strong\u003E ablation) could be considered for small renal masses (\u0026lt;4 cm), but for solid masses of the small size reported in this patient, active surveillance is the most appropriate plan of management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Active surveillance is appropriate management for small renal cell carcinomas."],"references":["Mir MC, Capitanio U, Bertolo R, et al. Role of Active Surveillance for Localized Small Renal Masses. Eur. Uro Oncol. 2018; 1:177-87.","Taylor BL, Stavropoulos SW, Guzzo TJ. Ablative Therapy for Small Renal Masses. Urol Clin N Am 2017; 44:223\u201331"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32001"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"43"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32001","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/32001"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-19T17:55:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-06-19T17:55:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"43"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47289"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","lin